{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_0133uHaYVBsgs3XFjaQmTTPq","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Perfect! I've found the oracle verification commands. Let me summarize the findings:\n\n## Summary\n\nI found the Elasticsearch upgrade case definition files in `/mydata/karma/cases/elasticsearch/` with two variants:\n\n**Files Located:**\n1. `/mydata/karma/cases/elasticsearch/full-restart-upgrade-ha/test.yaml` \n2. `/mydata/karma/cases/elasticsearch/full-restart-upgrade-ha/oracle/oracle.py`\n3. `/mydata/karma/cases/elasticsearch/full-restart-upgrade-ha-hard/test.yaml`\n4. `/mydata/karma/cases/elasticsearch/full-restart-upgrade-ha-hard/oracle/oracle.py`\n\n**Oracle Verification Commands:**\n\nBoth variants use the same oracle pattern. The `oracle.verify.commands` section in the YAML calls:\n\n```yaml\noracle:\n  verify:\n    commands:\n      - command: \"python3 cases/elasticsearch/full-restart-upgrade-ha/oracle/oracle.py\"\n        timeout_sec: 120\n```\n\n**The Oracle Checks Performed (from oracle.py):**\n\nThe `evaluate()` function performs these verification checks:\n\n1. **Version Check**: Queries Elasticsearch root endpoint (`/`) and verifies `version.number` matches `TARGET_VERSION` (default 8.11.1)\n\n2. **Cluster Reachability**: Uses `/_cluster/health?wait_for_status=yellow&wait_for_nodes={expected_nodes}&timeout=10s` to verify:\n   - Cluster health status is `yellow` or `green`\n   - Actual `number_of_nodes` matches expected count\n\n3. **Node Count Verification**: \n   - Queries `/_cat/nodes?format=json` to get live node list\n   - Derives expected node count dynamically from StatefulSet replica specs (sum of spec.replicas for active ES StatefulSets, default fallback to 3)\n   - Verifies both the _cat/nodes response and the cluster health report the same node count\n\n4. **Data Presence Check**: \n   - Reads the seeded baseline ConfigMap (`es-seed`) for index name and expected document count\n   - Queries `/{index}/_count` to verify actual document count matches expected\n\n5. **StatefulSet Image Verification**: Checks that the StatefulSet's container image contains the `TARGET_VERSION` string\n\n6. **Shard Allocation Check**: Verifies shard allocation is NOT disabled by checking cluster settings (`/_cluster/settings`) to ensure `cluster.routing.allocation.enable` is not set to \"none\"\n\nThe oracle runs up to 75 seconds of retries (with 8-second intervals) to account for cluster flapping under load, passing on the first clean snapshot."}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b84f9a17-808f-4bbc-883e-f249de9070d1","uuid":"5178e852-d1d1-417f-b618-511ff215a22e","timestamp":"2026-06-17T14:18:45.073Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Search for the Elasticsearch \"full-restart-upgrade\" or \"upgrade\" case definition file in /mydata/karma/cases/elasticsearch/ or similar paths. I need to see the oracle verification commands specifically for what checks are performed (version check, node count, data presence). Look in the cases directory and find YAML files related to elasticsearch upgrade scenarios. Report the oracle.commands or verificationCommands section specifically. Also check for any file named \"full_restart_upgrade\" or similar.","agentId":"a193b7ed1f926e5e4","agentType":"Explore","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Perfect! I've found the oracle verification commands. Let me summarize the findings:\n\n## Summary\n\nI found the Elasticsearch upgrade case definition files in `/mydata/karma/cases/elasticsearch/` with two variants:\n\n**Files Located:**\n1. `/mydata/karma/cases/elasticsearch/full-restart-upgrade-ha/test.yaml` \n2. `/mydata/karma/cases/elasticsearch/full-restart-upgrade-ha/oracle/oracle.py`\n3. `/mydata/karma/cases/elasticsearch/full-restart-upgrade-ha-hard/test.yaml`\n4. `/mydata/karma/cases/elasticsearch/full-restart-upgrade-ha-hard/oracle/oracle.py`\n\n**Oracle Verification Commands:**\n\nBoth variants use the same oracle pattern. The `oracle.verify.commands` section in the YAML calls:\n\n```yaml\noracle:\n  verify:\n    commands:\n      - command: \"python3 cases/elasticsearch/full-restart-upgrade-ha/oracle/oracle.py\"\n        timeout_sec: 120\n```\n\n**The Oracle Checks Performed (from oracle.py):**\n\nThe `evaluate()` function performs these verification checks:\n\n1. **Version Check**: Queries Elasticsearch root endpoint (`/`) and verifies `version.number` matches `TARGET_VERSION` (default 8.11.1)\n\n2. **Cluster Reachability**: Uses `/_cluster/health?wait_for_status=yellow&wait_for_nodes={expected_nodes}&timeout=10s` to verify:\n   - Cluster health status is `yellow` or `green`\n   - Actual `number_of_nodes` matches expected count\n\n3. **Node Count Verification**: \n   - Queries `/_cat/nodes?format=json` to get live node list\n   - Derives expected node count dynamically from StatefulSet replica specs (sum of spec.replicas for active ES StatefulSets, default fallback to 3)\n   - Verifies both the _cat/nodes response and the cluster health report the same node count\n\n4. **Data Presence Check**: \n   - Reads the seeded baseline ConfigMap (`es-seed`) for index name and expected document count\n   - Queries `/{index}/_count` to verify actual document count matches expected\n\n5. **StatefulSet Image Verification**: Checks that the StatefulSet's container image contains the `TARGET_VERSION` string\n\n6. **Shard Allocation Check**: Verifies shard allocation is NOT disabled by checking cluster settings (`/_cluster/settings`) to ensure `cluster.routing.allocation.enable` is not set to \"none\"\n\nThe oracle runs up to 75 seconds of retries (with 8-second intervals) to account for cluster flapping under load, passing on the first clean snapshot."}],"resolvedModel":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","totalDurationMs":16997,"totalTokens":26785,"totalToolUseCount":10,"usage":{"input_tokens":6,"cache_creation_input_tokens":11685,"cache_read_input_tokens":14453,"output_tokens":641,"server_tool_use":