{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_015VKRQBiYadW1vjv6bBeaYE","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"There's a data compatibility issue. The error is:\n```\nFormat version is not supported. Upgrading to [8.11.1] is only supported from version [7.17.0].\n```\n\nWait, but `7.17.9` IS at least `7.17.0`. This is confusing. Let me re-read:\n\n\"Upgrading to [8.11.1] is only supported from version [7.17.0].\"\n\nThis seems contradictory. The message says it's NOT supported from the current version in the PVC data. But `7.17.9 >= 7.17.0`.\nActually, I think I've been misreading this. The error likely means the data in the PVC was written by something older than 7.17.0, and 8.11.1 can only upgrade from 7.17.0 or later. But if the 7.17.9 pods crashed before writing any cluster state to the PVC, how would there be stale data from an incompatible version in there?\n\nThe PVC was fresh when the StatefulSet deployed, so 7.17.9 would have initialized it by creating the node directory structure and writing initial metadata files. However, the pods were crashing during SSL service initialization in XPackPlugin before they could fully start up and write cluster state.\n\nWhen 8.11.1 comes along and reads those partial 7.17.9-written files during NodeEnvironment initialization, it's rejecting them as unsupported, even though 7.17.9 should be a valid upgrade path. The version check seems to be failing despite 7.17.9 being >= 7.17.0.\n\nBut wait—the error is actually from `checkForIndexCompatibility`, which validates Lucene index format, not just ES version metadata. This suggests the PVCs might contain index files from a much older version that predates 7.17.0. Even though these PVCs were dynamically provisioned when the StatefulSet was created, they could have been pre-seeded with legacy data before the current deployment.\n\nLooking at the PVC creation timestamps (58 minutes ago), the 7.17.9 nodes did write metadata files during their brief runtime before the TLS crash. But the error message is oddly specific: \"Upgrading to [8.11.1] is only supported from version [7.17.0]\"—which suggests the stored format is from something older than 7.17.0. Given this is a multi-stage workflow called \"elasticsearch-long-transform-scale-upgrade\", the PVCs were likely seeded with data from an earlier stage using an older ES version.\n\nI need to either exec into a crashing pod or spin up a temporary pod mounting the data PVC to inspect what version actually wrote those metadata files. If the data is pre-7.17.0, I can't jump directly to 8.11.1—I'd need to either clear the PVCs and start fresh, or find another path forward.\n\nActually, thinking about this differently: the seeded `app-data` index lives in the main `es` cluster (es-0, es-1, es-2, es-data-0, es-data-1), not in the `es-cluster` PVCs. Since the precondition ran after all the StatefulSets were created and seeded data through the `es` cluster, the `es-cluster` PVCs don't have that index at all. That means I can safely wipe the `es-cluster` PVCs and let those nodes start fresh at 8.11.1, then they'll join as clean data nodes and the `app-data` index will replicate across.\n\nFor clearing the PVCs, I could add an init container to the `es-cluster` StatefulSet that removes the data directory before Elasticsearch starts, or I could spin up a temporary pod that mounts each PVC and clears it out. The init container approach is probably cleaner since it's self-contained. Writing shell commands...\n\nI need to scale the StatefulSet down to zero first to release the PVCs, then clean the data directories, and finally scale back up to restart with fresh state. The `es-cluster` pods were actually running at 7.17.9 when the precondition checked, but then the `es-config` was updated to require TLS (likely by a later step or adversary), forcing the pods to restart and fail due to missing SSL certificates. The precondition's count of 8 Running pods might have been captured before this config change took effect, or the pods were still technically Running at that moment despite the impending failure. The seed operations created the initial data through the `es-http` service, routing to the `es-data` pods and the `es` cluster. So the adversary's actions—corrupting the password secret and modifying the config to enforce TLS—happened after the precondition verified all 8 pods were running, which means `es-cluster` was definitely operational at that point before the TLS requirement broke it. So `es-cluster` has been stuck in CRASHLOOPBACKOFF the whole time, while the main `es` cluster at 8.11.1 is running fine with the seeded data. The PVCs for `es-cluster` likely contain data from an older ES version, which is why the upgrade to 8.11.1 fails with that format version error. My plan is to scale `es-cluster` down to zero and clear out the PVC data.\n\nI'm considering a few approaches—an init container would be risky since it'd wipe data on every restart, so instead I'll run a temporary cleanup job to remove the incompatible files from each PVC, then scale the cluster back up to 3 replicas. But first, let me verify this theory by spinning up a temporary pod to inspect what's actually stored in those PVCs.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2574,"cache_read_input_tokens":78419,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2574},"output_tokens":22,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b84f9a17-808f-4bbc-883e-f249de9070d1","uuid":"6a991896-e8e0-4938-ae71-8f7f341c9fb5","request_id":"req_011Cc8ys37Q5KNopDUMGH12R"}
